  "text": "The three mitosis-specific YAP phosphorylation sites matched the consensus site for cyclin-dependent kinase 1 (CDK1), a kinase that regulates many proteins that control mitosis. Moreover, the timing of YAP phosphorylation after release from nocodazole or double thymidine block is reminiscent of other CDK substrates, with greater phosphorylation at the entry of mitosis followed by dephosphorylation upon exit from mitosis (Figs. 3F and 4C). Indeed, short-term treatment of nocodazole-blocked cells with the CDK inhibitors Puravanol A or BMI1026 [CITATION_1] prevented the YAP mobility shift (Fig. 4K) . Although an indirect role for CDK1 cannot be ruled out, these findings suggest that CDK1 regulates the phosphorylation of YAP at Ser 138 , Thr",
